    "markdown": "## MRI Foot Overview\n\n### Cadabams Diagnostics Difference: 3T Scanners, Same-Day Reports\n- \\*\\*3T magnet strength\\*\\* = twice the detail of standard 1.5T machines\n- \\*\\*Sub-millimetre slices\\*\\* reveal tiny tendon tears and hairline fractures\n- \\*\\*Radiologists on-site\\*\\* deliver reports within 4–6 hours\n### Quick Facts at a Glance\n- \\*\\*Duration:\\*\\* 20–30 minutes\n- \\*\\*Radiation:\\*\\* Zero\n- \\*\\*Pain:\\*\\* None\n- \\*\\*Walk-in or appointment:\\*\\* Both accepted\n\n## Risks & Limitations of MRI of The Foot\n\n### Contrast Dye Considerations\n- \\*\\*Gadolinium\\*\\* is safe in 99.9 % of patients\n- \\*\\*Kidney function test\\*\\* (eGFR) required if eGFR < 30\n### Claustrophobia & Metal Implants\n- \\*\\*Open-bore 3T scanner\\*\\* reduces claustrophobia\n- \\*\\*MRI-safe implants\\*\\* (titanium screws, modern joint replacements) are fine\n- \\*\\*Pacemakers & cochlear implants\\*\\* need screening first\n\n## Parameters Considered During an MRI of The Foot\n\n- \\*\\*Bone marrow signal\\*\\* – detects bruising, infection, tumour\n- \\*\\*Tendons & ligaments\\*\\* – checks for sprains, tears, degeneration\n- \\*\\*Plantar fascia & fat pads\\*\\* – evaluates thickness, inflammation\n- \\*\\*Joint spaces\\*\\* – cartilage loss, effusion\n- \\*\\*Neurovascular bundle\\*\\* – nerve entrapment, vessel compression\n\n## Reasons for Taking an MRI Foot\n\n### Diagnosing Fractures Missed on X-ray\nUp to 30 % of \\*\\*metatarsal stress fractures\\*\\* are invisible on initial X-rays. MRI FOOT spots bone oedema within 24–48 hours of injury.\n### Evaluating Soft-Tissue Masses\n- \\*\\*Ganglion cysts\\*\\* vs. \\*\\*giant-cell tumours\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Lipomas\\*\\* vs. \\*\\*malignant sarcomas\\*\\*\n- \\*\\*Synovial thickening\\*\\* in rheumatoid arthritis\n\n## Benefits of the examination\n\n- \\*\\*High-resolution soft-tissue detail\\*\\* – 0.4 mm slice thickness\n- \\*\\*No radiation exposure\\*\\* – safe for children and pregnant patients (after 1st trimester)\n- \\*\\*Multi-planar views\\*\\* – sagittal, coronal, axial, and 3-D reconstructions\n- \\*\\*Functional sequences\\*\\* – dynamic contrast to assess blood flow\n\n## Illnesses Diagnosed with MRI Foot\n\n| Condition | What MRI Shows |\n|-----------|----------------|\n| \\*\\*Lisfranc injuries\\*\\* | Ligament disruption, subtle fractures |\n| \\*\\*Osteomyelitis\\*\\* | Bone marrow oedema, sinus tracts |\n| \\*\\*Morton’s neuroma\\*\\* | Enlarged interdigital nerve, bursitis |\n| \\*\\*Plantar plate tears\\*\\* | Discontinuity of fibrocartilage |\n| \\*\\*Talar dome osteochondral lesions\\*\\* | Cartilage delamination |\n\n## Preparing for MRI Foot\n\n### Clothing & Jewellery Guidelines\n- \\*\\*Wear cotton\\*\\* T-shirt and shorts or hospital gown\n- \\*\\*Remove\\*\\* watches, rings, toe rings, anklets\n- \\*\\*No metal zips, under-wires, or sequins\\*\\*\n### Fasting Rules (Only if Contrast Planned)\n- \\*\\*4-hour fast\\*\\* for solid food; clear fluids allowed\n- \\*\\*Hydrate well\\*\\* post-scan to flush gadolinium\n---\n## Pre-Requisites\n### Prior Imaging Comparison Disks\nBring \\*\\*CD or cloud link\\*\\* of previous X-ray, CT, or MRI for side-by-side comparison.\n### Kidney Function Tests for Contrast\n- \\*\\*Serum creatinine & eGFR\\*\\* within 30 days if > 60 years or diabetic\n- \\*\\*Instant eGFR\\*\\* available at Cadabams Diagnostics lab if needed\n---\n## Best Time to Take the MRI Foot\n### Early Morning Slots for Claustrophobic Patients\n- \\*\\*Less waiting\\*\\* = lower anxiety\n- \\*\\*Technologist can spend extra time\\*\\* explaining procedure\n### Avoid Scheduling During Acute Swelling\n- \\*\\*Severe oedema\\*\\* can blur soft-tissue detail\n- \\*\\*Wait 48–72 hours\\*\\* after acute sprain for clearer images\n---\n## Eligibility\n### Pediatric & Geriatric Suitability\n- \\*\\*Children > 5 years\\*\\* can usually cooperate; younger kids may need sedation\n- \\*\\*Elderly patients\\*\\* with joint replacements are routinely scanned\n### Pregnancy Guidelines\n- \\*\\*1st trimester:\\*\\* Avoid unless absolutely necessary\n- \\*\\*2nd & 3rd trimester:\\*\\* Safe with physician approval\n---\n## Procedure for Taking a MRI Foot\n1. \\*\\*Positioning:\\*\\* You lie feet-first into the scanner; a soft foam cushion supports the ankle.\n2. \\*\\*Coil placement:\\*\\* Dedicated 16-channel foot coil clicks gently around the foot.\n3. \\*\\*Earphones:\\*\\* Music or podcast to mask knocking sounds.\n4. \\*\\*Stillness:\\*\\* Keep foot motionless; each sequence lasts 3–5 minutes.\n5. \\*\\*Duration:\\*\\* 20–30 minutes total (add 10 minutes if contrast is used).\n---\n## Caution Before Taking the Test\n### MRI Safety Questionnaire\n- \\*\\*Tattoos:\\*\\* Inform if < 3 years old (some inks contain iron)\n- \\*\\*Implants:\\*\\* List all surgeries, even dental screws\n- \\*\\*Claustrophobia history:\\*\\* We offer mild sedation on request"
